[{"id":"VR787374","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a square and a right triangle. A coordinate system indicates that the x direction points horizontally to the right, the y direction points vertically upward, and the z direction points out of the page. The length of each side of the square is d, and the length of the triangle’s two legs are also d. The square and triangle are aligned so that each have one right angle corner at the intersection of the x and y axes. The square is labeled “E equals 2 times E sub 0, end sub, times i hat, plus E sub 0, end sub, times k hat.” The triangle is labeled “E sub 0, end sub, times i hat, plus 2 times E sub 0, end sub, times k hat.”\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR787374.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A square and a <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"45\"><math alttext=\"45\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>45</mn></math></span></span>-degree right triangle both lie in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x y\"><math alttext=\"x y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></math></span></span> plane in an <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x y z\"><math alttext=\"x y z\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></math></span></span> coordinate system, as shown in the figure. The lengths of the square’s sides and the triangle’s two legs are both equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span>. There are different uniform electric fields in the regions containing the square and the triangle. For the square, the electric field is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E sub square equals, 2 times E sub 0, end sub, times i hat, plus E sub 0, end sub, times k hat\"><math alttext=\"E sub square equals, 2 times E sub 0, end sub, times i hat, plus E sub 0, end sub, times k hat\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mtext>square</mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>k</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></mstyle></math></span></span>, and for the triangle the electric field is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E sub triangle equals, E sub 0, end sub, times i hat, plus 2 times E sub 0, end sub, times k hat\"><math alttext=\"E sub triangle equals, E sub 0, end sub, times i hat, plus 2 times E sub 0, end sub, times k hat\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mtext>triangle</mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>k</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></mstyle></math></span></span>. Which of the following statements has a correct claim comparing the electric flux magnitude through each area and also provides evidence or reasoning that helps support the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR787374_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The flux magnitude is the same for both shapes. The square and the triangle have the same field magnitude.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The flux magnitude is the same for both shapes. Compared to the square, the triangle has half the area and a field with twice the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"z\"><math alttext=\"z\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>z</mi></math></span></span>-component.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The flux magnitude is greater for the square than for the triangle. Compared to the triangle, the square has twice the area and the same field magnitude.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The flux magnitude is greater for the square than for the triangle. Both the area and the field component parallel to the plane of the shape is greater for the square.</p>"],"answer":1}]